# SAM-STGCN: Robust Abnormal Human Behavior Recognition with YOLOv8s and Spatial Attention

Official implementation for the paper:

This repository presents an abnormal human behavior recognition framework based on skeleton sequences.  
To improve robustness in complex surveillance scenes, we enhance the front-end human detection stage with **YOLOv8s** and introduce a **serial Spatial Attention Module (SAM)** after **ST-GCN** for spatial feature refinement.  
The method is designed for abnormal event recognition such as **falling** and **fighting**, especially under challenging conditions like **occlusion**, **crowded scenes**, and **illumination changes**. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

---

## Highlights

- **Robust skeleton extraction with YOLOv8s**
  - Replaces the traditional Tiny-YOLOv3 detector in the AlphaPose pipeline
  - Improves person localization under occlusion, strong light, and multi-person scenes :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

- **Serial Spatial Attention Module (SAM)**
  - Placed **after** ST-GCN feature extraction rather than parallel embedding
  - Dynamically emphasizes discriminative joints related to abnormal actions while suppressing redundant daily-motion noise :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

- **Improved abnormal behavior recognition**
  - Achieves strong performance on abnormal behavior benchmarks including **Le2i** and **ShanghaiTech**
  - Also shows good generalization on **NTU RGB+D 60** :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

---

## Framework Overview

Our pipeline consists of three stages:

1. **Human detection and pose estimation**
   - Use **YOLOv8s** to detect human regions of interest
   - Feed detected human instances into **AlphaPose** for 17-keypoint pose estimation
   - Construct an **18-joint skeleton** by adding the **neck joint** as the midpoint of the left and right shoulders :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

2. **Spatio-temporal feature extraction**
   - Use **ST-GCN** to model spatial topology and temporal motion dynamics of skeleton sequences :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}

3. **Spatial attention refinement**
   - Apply a lightweight **SAM** after ST-GCN
   - Use max pooling + mean pooling + convolution + sigmoid to generate spatial attention weights
   - Recalibrate node features and enhance critical joints for abnormal action recognition :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

---

## Method

### 1. YOLOv8s-enhanced skeleton extraction

Traditional top-down pose estimation pipelines often use Tiny-YOLOv3 as the front-end detector, but this can suffer from missed detections and inaccurate bounding boxes in complex surveillance scenarios.  
We replace it with **YOLOv8s**, which provides stronger robustness for:

- occluded pedestrians
- dense multi-person scenes
- distant small targets
- strong-light / night-time environments :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}

### 2. Serial SAM-STGCN architecture

Unlike conventional uniform feature aggregation in ST-GCN, our method inserts a **Spatial Attention Module (SAM)** after spatio-temporal graph convolution to refine spatial node representations.  
The SAM highlights discriminative joints related to abnormal motion patterns, such as:

- arms in fighting actions
- lower limbs and body center changes in falling actions :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

---

## Supported Datasets

### Le2i
The Le2i abnormal behavior dataset contains surveillance videos from scenes such as **Home**, **Coffee room**, **Office**, and **Lecture room**, with abnormal events including **falling** and **fighting**.  
The dataset contains **191 videos**, including **130 abnormal events**, with resolution **320×240**, frame rate **25 fps**, and around **24,000 frames**. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

### ShanghaiTech Campus
A representative benchmark for video anomaly detection, containing multiple campus scenes and both normal and abnormal events such as:

- fighting
- chasing
- falling down
- sudden running
- biking / cycling in pedestrian areas :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}

### NTU RGB+D 60
Used to evaluate the generalization ability of the proposed model on large-scale human action recognition. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}

---

## Experimental Settings

All experiments are implemented in **PyTorch** with **Python 3.8** and run on:

- Ubuntu
- Intel Core i5-12600KF
- NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4060 Ti (16GB)
- CUDA 11.8 :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}

Training settings:

- Optimizer: SGD with momentum
- Momentum: 0.9
- Batch size: 16
- Epochs: 100
- Initial learning rate: 0.01
- Weight decay: 0.0001
- Loss: Cross-Entropy / BCE depending on the task setting :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}

---

## Main Results

### Le2i abnormal behavior dataset

| Method | Accuracy (%) | Sensitivity (%) | Specificity (%) |
|------|------:|------:|------:|
| Lightweight ST-GCN | 96.1 | 92.5 | 95.7 |
| V2V-PoseNet | 93.7 | 100.0 | 87.0 |
| YOLOv7-DeepSORT | 94.5 | 98.6 | 97.0 |
| **Ours** | **96.42** | **98.8** | **99.1** |

Top-1 accuracy of our method reaches **96.42%** on Le2i. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}

### ShanghaiTech Campus dataset

| Method | Year | AUC (%) |
|------|------:|------:|
| Object-centric AE | 2019 | 78.7 |
| STAN | 2019 | 76.2 |
| SSMTL | 2020 | 82.4 |
| SSMTL++ | 2021 | 83.8 |
| Jigsaw-VAD | 2021 | 84.3 |
| VideoPatchCore | 2023 | 85.1 |
| **Ours** | **2026** | **85.1** |

Our method achieves **85.1% AUC** on ShanghaiTech. :contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}

### NTU RGB+D 60

| Method | CS (%) | CV (%) |
|------|------:|------:|
| ST-GCN | 81.5 | 88.3 |
| AS-GCN | 86.8 | 94.2 |
| 2s-AGCN | 88.5 | 95.1 |
| **Ours** | **87.5** | **94.4** |

The model also demonstrates good generalization on NTU RGB+D 60. :contentReference[oaicite:17]{index=17}

---

## Ablation Study

We evaluate the contribution of **YOLOv8s** and **SAM** on ShanghaiTech:

| Model | YOLOv8s | SAM | Accuracy (%) | AUC (%) |
|------|------|------|------:|------:|
| Baseline ST-GCN | No | No | 80.62 | 80.1 |
| Baseline + YOLOv8s | Yes | No | 83.37 | 84.1 |
| Baseline + SAM | No | Yes | 85.23 | 84.7 |
| **Ours** | **Yes** | **Yes** | **86.36** | **85.1** |

These results show that:
- YOLOv8s improves the robustness of skeleton extraction
- SAM enhances the discriminative representation of key joints
- The full model achieves the best overall performance :contentReference[oaicite:18]{index=18}

